# author: U-Zyn Chua <chua@uzyn.com>
# (Goose recipe schema does not support an author field)
version: "1.0.0"
title: "aimx email"
description: >
  Self-hosted email for AI agents. Send, read, reply to, and manage email
  via aimx MCP tools stored as Markdown files on the local filesystem.
extensions:
  - type: stdio
    name: aimx
    cmd: /usr/local/bin/aimx
    args:
      - mcp
    timeout: 300
    description: >
      aimx MCP server. Nine tools for mailbox and email operations.
prompt: |
  ## Wiring yourself up as a mailbox hook (Goose)

  When the user asks you to act on inbound mail automatically (for example
  "reply to anything that lands in `support@`"), create an `on_receive`
  hook that re-launches `goose run` with the email piped on stdin.

  Two recipes are supported. The recipe-based form is preferred for
  production because it pre-binds the `aimx mcp` extension and the
  inbound-email path:

  Production (recipe-based):

  ```
  hook_create(
    mailbox: "support",
    event: "on_receive",
    cmd: ["/usr/local/bin/goose", "run", "--recipe", "/etc/aimx/goose-aimx-hook.yaml"],
    stdin: "email"
  )
  ```

  `cmd[0]` must be an absolute path; the daemon refuses bare command
  names. The example uses `/usr/local/bin/goose`, which is typical for
  npm/curl installs. Adjust to match `which goose` on your host if
  the binary lives elsewhere (e.g. `/usr/bin/goose`).

  The referenced recipe pre-binds the `aimx` MCP extension and
  parameterizes `$AIMX_FILEPATH`. A minimal `/etc/aimx/goose-aimx-hook.yaml`:

  ```yaml
  version: "1.0.0"
  title: "aimx mailbox hook"
  description: "Read the inbound email and act on it via aimx MCP."
  extensions:
    - type: stdio
      name: aimx
      cmd: /usr/local/bin/aimx
      args: [mcp]
      timeout: 300
  prompt: |
    Read the email at the path in env var AIMX_FILEPATH and act on it
    via the aimx MCP server (e.g. email_reply or email_mark_read).
  ```

  Ad-hoc (direct prompt over stdin):

  ```
  hook_create(
    mailbox: "support",
    event: "on_receive",
    cmd: ["/usr/local/bin/goose", "run", "--instructions", "-", "--quiet"],
    stdin: "email"
  )
  ```

  `--instructions -` reads the prompt from stdin; the daemon pipes the
  raw email `.md` into that channel when `stdin: "email"` is set.
  `--quiet` keeps the run free of progress chatter that would otherwise
  pollute the structured log.

  Note: the user the hook runs as (the mailbox's owner) must have the
  aimx skill installed too — re-run `aimx agents setup goose` as that
  user before creating the hook, or the headless invocation will start
  without the skill loaded and the agent won't know what to do with the
  email.

